@node "Einfuehrung" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction:@{ub}@{par}@{b}=============@{ub}

@{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub}  is  a @{"MUI" link "MUI" 0} based backgammon game. This version is public domain,
so you can freely copy, change, and distribute it new.

You use @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} at your own risk, the @{"author" link "Autor" 0} isn`t responsible for any
damages, @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} possibly causes!

On  my  computer  the  program  never  caused  a bad fault, so I think, that
nothing  could  happen.  The  actual version hasn`t even caused a guru on my
computer yet.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Anforderungen" "Requirements"
@{b}Requirements:@{ub}@{par}@{b}=============@{ub}

@{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub}  should  work on all Amigas with WB 2.0, MUI 3.0 and better. I
programmed it on a 68000 with WB 3.1 and MUI 3.3.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@{b}Installation:@{ub}@{par}@{b}=============@{ub}

Just  copy the @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} drawer to a place which suits you. Nothing else
has to be done.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Aufruf" "Start"
@{b}Start:@{ub}@{par}@{b}======@{ub}

You can start @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} from either Workbench or Shell.

@{u}@{b}Starting from Workbench:@{ub}@{uu}

Switch  to the drawer, where @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} resides in and doubleclick on the
@{b}MUIbg@{ub}   icon.   There`s   a  tooltype  parameter,  called  @{b}FROM@{ub}, to select a
configuration file. The standard configuration file is @{b}ENV:MUIBackgammon@{ub}. If
you  save  a  configuration  file  with  an  icon,  than you`re even able to
doubleclick on that project icon.

@{u}@{b}Starting from Shell:@{ub}@{uu}

Switch  to  the @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub} drawer and tip in @{b}MUIbg@{ub} or type @{b}MUIbg@{ub} with the
absolute  path.  You  can use the @{b}FROM@{ub} parameter for loading a configuration
file.  If you type @{b}MUIbg ?@{ub}, the template will be shown. Well, just amigalike
;-)

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Benutzung" "Usage"
@{b}Usage:@{ub}@{par}@{b}======@{ub}

In  the  main  window you can find the @{"backgammon board" link "Spielbrett" 0}, some @{"buttons" link "Aktionsknoepfe" 0}, a few
@{"status displays" link "Statusanzeigen" 0} and a button to start the @{"configuration editor" link "Editor" 0}. There`s also
a @{"menu" link "Menue" 0} for extended configuration control of @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub}.

The  whole  game is very simple and intuitive. At the beginning the two dice
are  thrown,  the  first  one  for white (player1), the second one for black
(player2).  The  player with the biggest pip starts. The human player has to
click  on the start field first and than on the target field. If the move is
legal  it  will  be  shown  on the board, otherwise the screen will flash. I
hope,  that  I`ve implemented the official backgammon rules (if they exist).
Perhaps there`s somebody, who can email me a copy of them.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Spielbrett" "Board"
@{b}Board:@{ub}@{par}@{b}======@{ub}

The  backgammon  board consists of the well known three-cornered fields, the
two  bars  in the middle and the two target fields at the edge of the board.
If  you don`t like my favourite initial setting, don`t be sad. You can go to
the  @{"configuration editor" link "Editor" 0}  to  select  a new initial setting up for the four
components  of the backgammon board. Currently only six stones per field are
visible. Perhaps next time I implement a better graphical solution.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Aktionsknoepfe" "Buttons"
@{b}Buttons:@{ub}@{par}@{b}========@{ub}

@{b}Play:@{ub}  If  you don`t know which move to select, you can click on "Play", and
the computer calculates the next move.

@{b}Back:@{ub} Undo last move.

@{b}New:@{ub} Start a new game.

@{b}Modus:@{ub}  The  modus  can be "play": just playing backgammon, or "set": making
any move you want.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Statusanzeigen" "Status displays"
@{b}Status displays:@{ub}@{par}@{b}================@{ub}

Here you can see the messages of @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub}

@{b}Moves:@{ub} The number of moves left.

@{b}Rating:@{ub} The rating of the actual game position.

@{b}White target:@{ub} The number of white stones on the target field.

@{b}Black target:@{ub} The number of black stones on the target field.

@{b}List:@{ub} All other messages.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "Editor" "Configuration editor"
@{b}Configuration editor:@{ub}@{par}@{b}=====================@{ub}

@{b}@{u}General:@{uu}@{ub}

General settings of @{b}MUIBackgammon@{ub}

@{b}Player1:@{ub} The status of player1.

@{b}Player2:@{ub} The status of player2.

It`s possible to let the computer play versus himself.

@{b}Trace:@{ub}  "on"  means  that  the  computer waits for pressing the play button,
everytime he has to make the next move.

@{b}Level:@{ub}  Difficulty  level,  please  select the highest. It`s certain not too
difficult.



@{b}@{u}Board:@{uu}@{ub}

Configuration of the board.

@{b}Blink:@{ub} Number of the blinks, when the computer makes his move.

@{b}Blinktime:@{ub} Time between the blinks.

@{b}Boardtype:@{ub}  Type  of the board. To explain it, I use the abbrevaitions I for
white  homefield, II for white forefield, III for black forefield and IV for
black homefield, than the boardtype means: @{SETTABS 6 10}

0 =>@{TAB}III@{TAB}IV@{PAR} @{TAB}II@{TAB}I

1 =>@{TAB}IV@{TAB}III@{PAR} @{TAB}I@{TAB}II

2 =>@{TAB}II@{TAB}I@{PAR} @{TAB}III@{TAB}IV

3 =>@{TAB}I@{TAB}II@{PAR} @{TAB}IV@{TAB}III

I  hope,  that  I`ve considered every possible configuration. If there`s one
left, please email me.

@{b}White stones:@{ub} Colour of the white stones.

@{b}Black stones:@{ub} Colour of the black stones.

@{b}White fields:@{ub} Colour of the white fields. The fields will be dithert, so you
can  use  the same colours for the fields and the stones (Sorry, I`ve no gfx
card)

@{b}Black fields:@{ub} Colour of the black fields.



@{b}@{u}AI:@{uu}@{ub}

Configure the rating function

@{b}AI configuration:@{ub} Opens the @{"AI editor" link "KI-Editor"}.



@{b}@{u}Buttons:@{uu}@{ub}

Saving, loading, ...

@{b}Save:@{ub}  Saves  the configuration in @{b}ENVARC:MUIBackgammon@{ub}, so you can turn off
the  computer  and  the  next  time  you  play  the  game, you have the same
configuration.

@{b}Use:@{ub}  Saves  the  configuration  in  @{b}ENV:MUIBackgammon@{ub}, so you can leave the
program  and next time you start it, you have the same configuration. But if
you reset the computer you lose the configuration.

@{b}Load:@{ub} Loads the configuration from @{b}ENV:MUIBackgammon@{ub}.

@endnode

@REM------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node "KI-Editor" "AI editor"
@{b}AI editor:@{ub}@{par}@{b}==========@{ub}

Here you can configure the rating functions seperately for white and black.

@{b}Bar:@{ub} Points for stones on the bar.

@{b}Single:@{ub} Points for single stones.

@{b}SingleProb:@{ub}  Points  for  single stones in relation to the probability to be
stroken

@{b}Distance:@{ub} Points for distance from homefield.

@{b}Six:@{ub} Points for fields with six or more stones.

@{b}Block:@{ub} Points for blocks, groups of fields with two or more stones.

@{b}Target:@{ub} Points for stones on the target field.

@{b}Home:@{ub} Points for stones in the homefield.

@{b}Distribution:@{ub} Points for the distribution of the stones in the homefield.

If you e.g. decrease the number of the points for bar and single on the left
side  and  don`t  change  the  right  side  accordingly,  than you create an
aggressive player, who wants to harm the rival.

@endnode

